Subject:    <a href="?t=95837888300032&r=1&w=2">Plummer's proposal</a>
From:       <a href="?a=95837784000011&r=1&w=2">David C. Plummer &lt;DCP () QUABBIN ! SCRC ! Symbolics ! COM&gt;</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198608">1986-08-08 10:36:00</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837759026754&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837759026754&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

Another, somewhat small but important, reason for left rooting.
Consider completion in the fact of relative naming and mergine.
Completion without tree traversal works today.  With a default of
	Riverside.SCRC.Symbolics.COM
one can type
	Qua &lt;complete&gt;
and it is "obvious" it means complete "Qua" in the "SCRC.Symbolics.COM"
domain.  What isn't natural is something like
	Whi.SWW+ &lt;complete&gt;
Does this mean the host named "Whi" in the domain you get after
completing "SWW" in the "Symbolics.COM" domain, or does it mean complete
"Whi" in the "SWW.Symbolics.COM" domain.  The problem is that the thing
being completed is textually separated from the completion request.

With left rooting, it works similarly to our pathnames.  With a default
of
	.COM.Symbolics.SCRC.Riverside
one can type
	Qua &lt;complete&gt;
and get
	.COM.Symbolics.SCRC.Quabbin
or one can type
	+SWW.Whi &lt;complete&gt;
and complete the name "Whi" in the ".COM.Symbolics.SWW" domain.

I also agree with Benson: if we can't enforce separating the message
from the envelope, we better make the network format person-friendly.

